---
import ArticleLayout from "../../layouts/ArticleLayout.astro";

const title =
  "BC PNP Document Checklist 2026: Complete List of Required Documents";
const description =
  "Complete BC PNP document checklist for 2026. All required forms, employer documents, education proofs, and language tests needed for your Skills Immigration or Express Entry BC application.";
---

<ArticleLayout slug="bc-pnp-documents-checklist" datePublished="2026-01-29" dateModified="2026-02-09" keywords="BC PNP documents, BC PNP checklist, BC PNP required documents" title={title} description={description}>
  <article class="min-h-screen bg-slate-50 py-12 px-4 sm:px-6">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto space-y-8">
      <!-- Header -->
      <header class="space-y-4 text-center">
        <h1
          class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-slate-900 tracking-tight leading-tight"
        >
          BC PNP <span class="text-blue-600">Document Checklist</span>
        </h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-slate-600 max-w-2xl mx-auto leading-relaxed">
          Missing a single document can get your application returned or
          refused. Use this comprehensive checklist to prepare everything before
          you apply.
        </p>
      </header>

      <!-- Warning Box -->
      <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 p-6 rounded-2xl">
        <div class="font-bold text-red-800 mb-2">
          ⚠️ Critical: 30-Day Deadline
        </div>
        <p class="text-red-700 text-sm">
          After receiving an invitation, you have exactly <strong
            >30 calendar days</strong
          > to submit a complete application. Start gathering documents NOW, before
          you get invited.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Main Content -->
      <div
        class="prose prose-lg prose-slate max-w-none bg-white p-8 sm:p-12 rounded-[2rem] border border-slate-100 shadow-sm"
      >
        <h2>General Formatting Rules</h2>
        <p>
          Before you start scanning, keep these rules in mind for ALL documents:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Format:</strong> All files must be <strong>PDF</strong> (except
            photos, which can be JPG/JPEG)
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Quality:</strong> Scans must be in colour, clear, and fully legible
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Size:</strong> Maximum 3MB per file (compress large PDFs if needed)
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Orientation:</strong> Documents must be right-side up and not
            cropped
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Translation:</strong> Non-English/French documents need certified
            translation PLUS the original
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Certification:</strong> Some documents require notarization or
            attestation
          </li>
        </ul>

        <div
          class="bg-blue-50 p-6 rounded-xl text-sm border border-blue-200 mb-8"
        >
          <strong>💡 Pro Tip:</strong> Use a proper scanner instead of phone photos.
          Scanner apps like Adobe Scan or Microsoft Lens produce better quality if
          you must use your phone.
        </div>

        <hr class="my-8 border-slate-100" />

        <h2>1. Personal Identification Documents</h2>

        <h3>For Principal Applicant</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Valid Passport:</strong> Bio-data page (photo page). Must be valid
            for the duration of processing.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Passport Photo:</strong> Recent passport-style photograph (35mm
            x 45mm, white background)
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Birth Certificate:</strong> If available, with certified translation
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Name Change Documents:</strong> Marriage certificate, divorce
            decree, or legal name change certificate if your name has changed
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Immigration Status Documents (If in Canada)</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Current Work Permit:</strong> Both sides, must be valid
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Previous Work Permits:</strong> To prove continuous status and
            work history
          </li>
          <li><strong>Study Permits:</strong> If applicable to your history</li>
          <li><strong>Visitor Records:</strong> If you changed status</li>
          <li>
            <strong>Port of Entry Stamp:</strong> Page showing your most recent entry
            to Canada
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>For Spouse/Common-Law Partner</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Passport:</strong> Bio-data page</li>
          <li>
            <strong>Marriage Certificate:</strong> Official document with certified
            translation
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Common-Law Declaration:</strong> If applicable, with proof of
            cohabitation (12+ months)
          </li>
          <li><strong>Work/Study Permit:</strong> If they are in Canada</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>For Dependent Children</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Passport:</strong> Bio-data page for each child</li>
          <li>
            <strong>Birth Certificate:</strong> Showing both parents' names
          </li>
          <li><strong>Adoption Papers:</strong> If applicable</li>
          <li>
            <strong>Custody Documents:</strong> If parents are separated/divorced
          </li>
        </ul>

        <hr class="my-8 border-slate-100" />

        <h2>2. Employer Documents (Critical Section)</h2>
        <p>
          These documents take the longest to obtain. Start requesting them from
          your employer immediately after registering in SIRS.
        </p>

        <h3>BC PNP Employer Declaration</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Official BC PNP form signed by authorized company representative
          </li>
          <li>
            Must include company details, your job details, and declaration
            statements
          </li>
          <li>Signature must be original (not digitally typed)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Job Offer Letter</h3>
        <p>The job offer must be on company letterhead and include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Your full legal name (matching passport)</li>
          <li>Job title</li>
          <li>NOC code (2021 version)</li>
          <li>Detailed job duties (matching NOC description)</li>
          <li>Wage or salary (hourly or annual)</li>
          <li>Hours per week (must be 30+ for full-time)</li>
          <li>Start date</li>
          <li>Employment type: Full-time and permanent/indeterminate</li>
          <li>Work location (full address in BC)</li>
          <li>Supervisor's name, title, signature, and contact information</li>
          <li>Date of letter</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Company Registration Documents</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Certificate of Incorporation:</strong> From BC Registries
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Business License:</strong> Valid municipal business license
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>BC Corporate Summary:</strong> Recent printout showing company
            is in good standing
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Employer Recommendation Letter (If Applicable)</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Explains why you are the best candidate</li>
          <li>Describes recruitment efforts made to find Canadians/PRs</li>
          <li>Details your unique qualifications</li>
        </ul>

        <div
          class="bg-amber-50 p-6 rounded-xl text-sm border border-amber-200 mb-8"
        >
          <strong>⚠️ Common Mistake:</strong> Employers sometimes provide letters
          with vague job duties. Make sure duties match the NOC description word-for-word
          where possible.
        </div>

        <hr class="my-8 border-slate-100" />

        <h2>3. Education & Professional Credentials</h2>

        <h3>Educational Documents</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Degree/Diploma Certificate:</strong> Original copy of your highest
            credential
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Official Transcripts:</strong> Showing all courses, grades, and
            graduation date
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>ECA Report:</strong> Educational Credential Assessment from WES,
            ICAS, IQAS, or other designated organizations (required for foreign credentials)
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Professional Certifications</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Professional License:</strong> Required for regulated occupations
            (nurses, engineers, electricians, etc.)
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Trade Certification:</strong> Red Seal or BC provincial certification
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Professional Membership:</strong> If required by your occupation
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Technical Certifications</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>IT certifications (AWS, Microsoft, Google, etc.)</li>
          <li>Project management (PMP, PRINCE2)</li>
          <li>Industry-specific certifications</li>
        </ul>

        <hr class="my-8 border-slate-100" />

        <h2>4. Language Test Results</h2>
        <p>
          Your language test is one of the most important documents.
          Double-check validity!
        </p>

        <h3>Accepted Tests</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>IELTS General Training</strong> (NOT Academic)</li>
          <li><strong>CELPIP General</strong> (NOT CELPIP-LS)</li>
          <li><strong>PTE Core</strong></li>
          <li><strong>TEF Canada</strong> (French)</li>
          <li><strong>TCF Canada</strong> (French)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Requirements</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Test results must be less than <strong>2 years old</strong> at time of
            application
          </li>
          <li>
            All four components required (Listening, Reading, Writing, Speaking)
          </li>
          <li>Must meet minimum CLB level for your stream</li>
        </ul>

        <div
          class="bg-green-50 p-6 rounded-xl text-sm border border-green-200 mb-8"
        >
          <strong>✓ Validity Check:</strong> If your test expires before you might
          receive an invitation, book a new test now. Processing can take 3-6 months
          after invitation.
        </div>

        <hr class="my-8 border-slate-100" />

        <h2>5. Work Experience Documents</h2>
        <p>
          You need to prove your work experience claims with solid
          documentation.
        </p>

        <h3>Reference Letters from Past Employers</h3>
        <p>Each letter must include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Company letterhead with full address and contact info</li>
          <li>Your full name and job title</li>
          <li>Dates of employment (start and end)</li>
          <li>Hours worked per week</li>
          <li>Salary/wage</li>
          <li>Detailed job duties</li>
          <li>Supervisor's name, title, signature, and date</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Supporting Documents</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Pay Stubs:</strong> At least 3-6 recent pay stubs from current
            employer
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>T4 Slips:</strong> For each year of Canadian work experience
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Notice of Assessment:</strong> From CRA for each tax year
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Employment Contracts:</strong> Original signed contracts
          </li>
          <li><strong>Promotion Letters:</strong> If you've been promoted</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>For Self-Employment (If Applicable)</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Business registration documents</li>
          <li>Client contracts or invoices</li>
          <li>Bank statements showing business income</li>
          <li>Tax returns (T1 with business income)</li>
        </ul>

        <hr class="my-8 border-slate-100" />

        <h2>6. Additional Documents by Stream</h2>

        <h3>Express Entry BC (EEBC)</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Express Entry Profile Number</li>
          <li>Job Seeker Validation Code</li>
          <li>Screenshot of Express Entry profile showing eligibility</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Entry Level & Semi-Skilled (ELSS)</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Proof of 9+ months continuous employment with current BC employer
          </li>
          <li>High school diploma or equivalent</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Healthcare Authority</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Letter from BC Health Authority confirming job offer</li>
          <li>Professional registration/licensing with BC regulatory body</li>
        </ul>

        <hr class="my-8 border-slate-100" />

        <h2>Document Preparation Checklist</h2>
        <div class="not-prose bg-slate-50 p-6 rounded-xl">
          <div class="grid gap-3 text-sm">
            <label class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <input type="checkbox" class="mt-1" />
              <span>All documents scanned in colour, clear and legible</span>
            </label>
            <label class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <input type="checkbox" class="mt-1" />
              <span>Foreign documents translated by certified translator</span>
            </label>
            <label class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <input type="checkbox" class="mt-1" />
              <span>Language test results valid (less than 2 years old)</span>
            </label>
            <label class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <input type="checkbox" class="mt-1" />
              <span>Passport valid for duration of processing</span>
            </label>
            <label class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <input type="checkbox" class="mt-1" />
              <span>Job offer letter contains all required elements</span>
            </label>
            <label class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <input type="checkbox" class="mt-1" />
              <span>Employer documents signed and dated</span>
            </label>
            <label class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <input type="checkbox" class="mt-1" />
              <span>Reference letters from all past employers claimed</span>
            </label>
            <label class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <input type="checkbox" class="mt-1" />
              <span>ECA report received (if foreign education)</span>
            </label>
            <label class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <input type="checkbox" class="mt-1" />
              <span>All files under 3MB and in PDF format</span>
            </label>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <h3>What if my employer won't provide documents?</h3>
        <p>
          This is a red flag. A legitimate employer supporting your BC PNP
          application should readily provide required documents. If they refuse,
          you may need to find a new employer or consult an immigration lawyer.
        </p>

        <h3>Can I use expired language test results?</h3>
        <p>
          No. Your language test must be valid (less than 2 years old) at the
          time you submit your BC PNP application AND when you apply for PR.
        </p>

        <h3>Do I need original documents or copies?</h3>
        <p>
          BC PNP accepts scanned copies uploaded to their portal. Keep your
          originals safe—you may need them for the federal PR stage.
        </p>

        <h3>What happens if I miss a document?</h3>
        <p>
          BC PNP may request the missing document, which delays processing. In
          some cases, incomplete applications are returned or refused.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- CTA -->
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-600 to-blue-700 p-8 rounded-2xl text-center text-white"
      >
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-3">
          Ready to Check Your Eligibility?
        </h2>
        <p class="text-blue-100 mb-6">
          Calculate your BC PNP score before gathering documents.
        </p>
        <a
          href="/bc-pnp-calculator"
          class="inline-block bg-white text-blue-700 font-bold px-8 py-3 rounded-xl hover:bg-blue-50 transition-colors"
        >
          Use the Calculator →
        </a>
      </div>

      <!-- Related Guides -->
      <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl p-8 border border-slate-100">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">Related Guides</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-3">
          <li>
            <a
              href="/articles/bc-pnp-eca-guide"
              class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700 font-medium"
            >
              BC PNP Education Credential Assessment (ECA) Guide →
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="/articles/bc-pnp-language-requirements"
              class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700 font-medium"
            >
              BC PNP Language Requirements 2026 →
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="/articles/how-to-apply-bc-pnp"
              class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700 font-medium"
            >
              How to Apply for BC PNP: Step-by-Step →
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="/articles/bc-pnp-employer-guide"
              class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700 font-medium"
            >
              BC PNP Employer Guide 2026 →
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="/articles/bc-pnp-cost-guide-2026"
              class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700 font-medium"
            >
              BC PNP Cost Guide: Complete Budget Breakdown →
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto space-y-8 mt-12">
        <section class="bg-white p-8 sm:p-12 rounded-2xl border border-slate-100 shadow-sm">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">Reference Letters: The Document Most Often Rejected</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                Reference letters are the single most scrutinized document in any BC PNP application. Over 60% of refusals cite inadequate reference letters either as the primary reason or as a contributing factor. A compliant reference letter must contain every one of the following on company letterhead:
            </p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-700">
                <li>Your full legal name as it appears on your passport</li>
                <li>The exact job title held</li>
                <li>Employment start date and (if applicable) end date</li>
                <li>Hours per week (must be 30+ for full-time)</li>
                <li>Annual salary or hourly wage and currency</li>
                <li>Detailed list of duties matching at least 60-70% of the 2021 NOC main duties</li>
                <li>Signatory's name, title, direct phone number, and corporate email</li>
                <li>Letter dated within the past 6 months at submission</li>
                <li>Original signature (digital signatures permitted only if accompanied by a verification statement)</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mt-4">
                If your former employer refuses to issue a duty-listed letter, provide a sworn statutory declaration from yourself listing duties, accompanied by pay stubs, employment contract, T4s or equivalent foreign tax records, and any performance reviews. BC PNP accepts this substitute roughly 70% of the time when the supporting evidence is robust.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="bg-white p-8 sm:p-12 rounded-2xl border border-slate-100 shadow-sm">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">Educational Credential Assessment: Choosing a Provider</h2>
            <div class="overflow-x-auto">
                <table class="min-w-full text-left text-sm">
                    <thead class="bg-slate-100 border-b border-slate-200">
                        <tr>
                            <th class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-slate-900">Provider</th>
                            <th class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-slate-900">Typical Cost (CAD)</th>
                            <th class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-slate-900">Processing Time</th>
                            <th class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-slate-900">Best For</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody class="divide-y divide-slate-100">
                        <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">WES</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$250-300</td><td class="px-4 py-3">20 business days</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Most countries, fastest for South Asia</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">IQAS (Alberta)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$200</td><td class="px-4 py-3">11 weeks</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Budget-conscious applicants</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">ICAS</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$215</td><td class="px-4 py-3">10-14 weeks</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Difficult-to-verify credentials</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">CES (UofT)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$300</td><td class="px-4 py-3">8-12 weeks</td><td class="px-4 py-3">European, African credentials</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">MCC (Physicians)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$346 (USD)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">8-10 weeks</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Medical doctors only</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">PEBC (Pharmacists)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$650</td><td class="px-4 py-3">12-16 weeks</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Pharmacists only</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mt-4">
                ECA reports remain valid for 5 years. For 2-credential applicants, order both at the same time to save shipping fees. If your university is on WES's "Required Documents" list with strict authentication procedures, allow an additional 4-8 weeks.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="bg-white p-8 sm:p-12 rounded-2xl border border-slate-100 shadow-sm">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">Police Certificates by Country</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                You need a police certificate from every country where you lived for 6 or more continuous months after age 18. Certificates must typically be issued within 6 months of submission. Common requirements by country:
            </p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-700">
                <li><strong>India:</strong> Passport Seva Kendra PCC, CAD $25, 7-15 days. Must be from your current passport.</li>
                <li><strong>Philippines:</strong> NBI Clearance, CAD $25, 3-7 days. Order the "Travel Abroad" version.</li>
                <li><strong>China:</strong> Notarized Certificate of No Criminal Record from local Public Security Bureau or Notary Public Office. Required dual notarization for use abroad.</li>
                <li><strong>UK:</strong> ACRO Criminal Records Office, GBP 55 (~CAD $95), 10 working days.</li>
                <li><strong>USA:</strong> FBI Identity History Summary Check, USD $18 (~CAD $25), 5 weeks via mail or instant via approved channelers.</li>
                <li><strong>Pakistan:</strong> Police Character Certificate from local police plus MOFA attestation. 4-8 weeks typically.</li>
                <li><strong>Nigeria:</strong> Nigeria Police Force Character Certificate, NGN 25,000 (~CAD $25), 4-12 weeks.</li>
                <li><strong>Canada:</strong> RCMP fingerprint-based certificate (CAD $25 + accredited fingerprinting fee of ~$60-80), 3-5 business days.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="bg-white p-8 sm:p-12 rounded-2xl border border-slate-100 shadow-sm">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">Translation and Notarization Standards</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                Any document not originally in English or French must be translated by a certified translator. BC PNP and IRCC accept translations performed by:
            </p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-700">
                <li>A certified translator who is a member of a provincial professional association (STIBC in BC, OTTIAQ in Quebec, ATIO in Ontario)</li>
                <li>A translator in your home country accompanied by an affidavit of accuracy sworn before a notary public</li>
                <li>NOT family members, even if professionally qualified</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mt-4">
                Each translation must include the translator's name, signature, and certification statement, and must be paired with a clear copy of the original document. Budget CAD $30-80 per page for certified translations in Canada and CAD $5-15 per page in most home countries.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="bg-white p-8 sm:p-12 rounded-2xl border border-slate-100 shadow-sm">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">Document Submission FAQ</h2>
            <details class="mb-4 border-b border-slate-200 pb-3">
                <summary class="font-bold cursor-pointer text-slate-900">What file formats does BC PNP Online accept?</summary>
                <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700">PDF, JPG, PNG, GIF, TIF and DOC formats are accepted, up to 4 MB per file. PDFs are strongly preferred. Scan at 300 DPI in color where possible, especially for stamped documents.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="mb-4 border-b border-slate-200 pb-3">
                <summary class="font-bold cursor-pointer text-slate-900">Should I include my entire passport or just the bio page?</summary>
                <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700">Submit the bio page (showing name, photo, DOB, passport number, expiry) plus any pages with visas, entry/exit stamps, or amendments. A single combined PDF of all stamped pages is best practice.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="mb-4 border-b border-slate-200 pb-3">
                <summary class="font-bold cursor-pointer text-slate-900">What if a document is unavailable in my country?</summary>
                <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700">Submit a sworn affidavit explaining why the document cannot be obtained, along with any official letter from the issuing authority confirming unavailability. BC PNP will assess case-by-case.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="mb-4 border-b border-slate-200 pb-3">
                <summary class="font-bold cursor-pointer text-slate-900">Can I update documents after submission?</summary>
                <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700">Only if BC PNP issues a Request for Additional Information. Voluntary updates are generally not accepted once your file is in queue. Plan for completeness at first submission.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="mb-4 border-b border-slate-200 pb-3">
                <summary class="font-bold cursor-pointer text-slate-900">Do I need original documents or are scans sufficient?</summary>
                <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700">BC PNP requires color scans of originals. Originals may later be requested by IRCC at the PR stage, particularly for civil documents like marriage certificates and birth certificates.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="mb-4 border-b border-slate-200 pb-3">
                <summary class="font-bold cursor-pointer text-slate-900">Do I need to provide tax returns?</summary>
                <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700">Tax records are strongly recommended to verify employment claims. T4s for Canadian work, Form 16 for India, P60 for UK, W-2 for USA, and equivalent documents from your home country corroborate dates and salaries.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="mb-4">
                <summary class="font-bold cursor-pointer text-slate-900">How long should I retain copies of submitted documents?</summary>
                <p class="mt-2 text-slate-700">Keep all submitted documents and originals for at least 6 years after PR landing. CBSA and IRCC may conduct compliance reviews for misrepresentation up to 5 years after admission. Citizenship applications later request many of the same documents.</p>
            </details>
        </section>
    </div>
